Print one of everything. I did .2 and 25% infill with PLA. I didn't split the back because it would fit on my printer as one piece.

Matt

title: Wanhao Duplicator i3 v2.1 Z-probe bracket for BLTouch

description.text:
This is a z-probe bracket for the Wanhao Duplicator i3 v2.1, with probe hole spacing intended specifically for the BLTouch probe.

It's intended specifically for the i3 v2, as it's designed to fit around the newer rounded bearings of the x-axis carriage. I got the idea for attaching the bracket to the lower bearing bolts from rativiv's BLTouch mount (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2042894), but I was unhappy with the fact that his mount resulted in a probe offset of about 55mm back and 20mm to the right. It meant that I couldn't measure and compensate for the distortion of the front 55mm of my print surface.

This bracket uses the same mounting holes, but places the probe directly underneath the print nozzle of the i3, meaning that you can measure the entire print surface. It does, of course, mean that you have to install/remove the probe when you want to measure/print, but I just use 4 x m4 wing nuts to hold the bracket during measurement.

Personally, I milled this part out of standard 4.7752mm aluminum stock in order to keep it light and rigid, but you could just as easily print it out of PLA. You might need to enlarge the 4 bearing bolt holes if you print it, since I kept the tolerances very tight in order to minimize slop.

This Thing provides a way to mount 30cm flexible LED strips, like these ones from EBay :

There are files for single, dual and triple banks of strips.

For each mount, you'll need :

Hardware :
30cm LED Strip/s
1 X 15mm M3 bolt
1 X M3 nut
ABS Glue (or Superglue if you're using PLA)

Printed Parts :
1 X MountWithEndCap (Single, Dual or Triple)
1 X MountWithNoEndCap (Single, Dual or Triple)
1 X Holder (Single, Dual or Triple)
1 X Swivel Set (Standard or tall)

I printed my parts in ABS, and used some ABS glue to stick all the parts together. It would also work just fine with PLA, using SuperGlue to assemble.

I'm sure there's some funky way to use interlocking parts to put it all together, but my 3D modelling skills just aren't that good :)

I've included a few different swivel sets for some flexibility.

I did have a go at a diffuser, which didn't really work with white ABS, but I've included the files anyway - would love to see how it goes with some transparent filament, so if you have some, please give it a go and let me know how it came out.

To assemble, glue the two channels end to end into the holder. Make sure the end cap is at an end, not the middle!

Glue the head of the swivel set (the part with a single flange) to the centre on the back of the holder.

Insert the head of the swivel into the base and fasten the M3 bolt.

description.text:
Replacement linear bearings for the carriage.
45mm long, so twice the length of the original metal LM10UU or drylin 10mm linear bearings. These have no slop on the rods and are a tight fit.
They are less than half the weight of the original holders and metal bearings.

Ive included 8mm versions because I could.
They have no use on the Geeetech mini delta.

I designed these longer bearings as an alternative to adding an additional bearing and increasing the size of the carriage. The longer bearings did not fit the existing plastic bearing holders so I incorporated the holder into the design as one piece ready to bolt in place with the existing m5 nuts and bolts.

Ive included simple printing supports in the design. You can add support material with your slicer but I found Nylon didnt need any extra support.

I have printed these in Taulman Bridge Nylon and they are a great fit and there is no slop in the bearings. Once reamed they ran freely on the rod.

Update: 13 Aug 2017.
The 10mm bearings stl is a very tight fit on the 10mm rods on my Geeetech G2S pro.
I reamed them with a 10mm straight cut reamer but still too tight and sticking.
I either need to ream them a little bigger or print with more clearance on the internal diameter. Awkward and time consuming to test as Im using the machine and have to dismantle it each time to test.

I need to be clear J3D ONLY designed the base and nameplate. The Monty Foot STL was already created by Ceberus333 at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:43025.

Tinkercad font options are very limiting so I laid out the text in text boxes in PowerPoint using a font called Apple Chancery. Took a screen shot of that, exported it as a JPG and then uploaded that to https://www.selva3d.com to create the STL file. Pulled that STL file with the Apple Chancery font into Tinkercad, placed it on a baseplate and grouped it.

This font is finely detailed and the quality of the print varied quite a bit. But the settings were 200 mi resolution with 5% infill, True white PLA for the base and True Black for the font.

After the parts were printed and painted, glued it all together with Loctite. $4.99 a bottle at Home Depot.

description.text:
Update 3: Going to V4. Main changes here are extrusion multiplier dropped a bit and completely reworked my start up / bed level routine. I've had a lot better looking first layers by using a 0.4mm first layer (double what I had before) and doing the full 6x6 grid bed level routine. I never had any bed adhesion issues with my last setup, but often the first layer just didn't look nice. I also added some pauses around the bed level routine to give time to clean any residue off the bed and nozzle.

Update 2: I've tweaked my settings a bit more and honestly can't remember what all I've changed. I lowered my speeds just a touch to help with overall quality and tweaked my retraction to help eliminate stringing. This V3 config will probably be the last I upload since I'm pretty happy with everything.

Update: I've been tweaking my settings over the last few days and have changed a lot of little things to help with stringing, bridging, and overall quality. My heated bed has warped a bit so I changed the auto bed level to do a 3x3 grid. You still go to the same line to adjust the first layer height, it has just changed a bit to: "G29 P3 Z0.4 ;If your..."
You can change the "P3" to "P5", or "P6" if you want even more auto level points to be tested.

Here is my config file for Slic3r Prusa Edition. It is working really good for me on my Monoprice Mini Delta. If your first layer height isn't right then go to the "print settings tab" then select "custom G-code" and under the start G-code scroll down to the line:
"G29 C-0.8 Z0.4 ; if your first layer is too far from the bed then lower the Z number, if it is to close, then raise it."

The comment is pretty self explanatory, but changing to Z0.3 will make the first layer closer ot the bed and Z0.5 will make it further...

OpenForge
=========
Dungeon edge corridor tiles designed to be compatible with Dwarven Forge dungeon tiles.
These tiles are designed to line their wall up with walls from tiles butted up against their neighbors. These are designed to be used on the edge of the map or to give more usable space for the play area, particularly for 1x hallways which would be impossible to fit mins in unless the wall was moved. Because the wall now takes up some space, you will need to use edge buffers in some places to get the tiles to lay out properly.
You can find this set on github

  • Smooth Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc.
  • Smooth Edge Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc. Edge tiles.

Hate that buzzing noise when you accidentally touch the blades of that super-speedy mag-lev fan? Is the tip of your nose now slightly shorter than yesterday? Do I have a solution for you!

Cons:

description.text:
So i took the original portal gun by 3DCentralVA and changed the handle on it. I changed it to match the original from the series. This will print in a single piece upside down. I also made a green energy plasma ball for the center.

I modified Thing 153978 to work as a Manfrotto 200PL quick release plate. This should work on any Manfrotto head which uses the RC2 system. It also works on my older Manfrotto 3160 head.

Manfro200PL.thrd.stl has a threaded hole. The thumb screw shaft is not threaded at its base, so it threads in and then turns freely, but won't fall out. Manfro200PL.Padeclip.stl has a large hole with no threads, so an e-clip retainer holds the thumb screw in. I printed with 40% infill and seven shells. I printed right side up with support so the recessed areas on top for the e-clip and rubber pad (inner tube) stay tidy. But it's probably better to print upside down with support and then remove the trivial support from the top surface so it's a rough surface for gluing the rubber pad on. If the long dimension is 53 mm, it fits snugly in the tripod head, and may need a corner shaved off for easy insertion.
Even when printed in ABS, this will not be as strong as metal ones, so using with big video cameras or huge lenses is not recommended.

title: D810 2040 extruder and spool mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A spool holder to mount on the 2040 extrusion at the top of my Zonestar D810 delta, and an associated extruder mount. This makes the spool holder and extruder much more accessible for changing filament, and shortens the Bowden tube quite a bit. The spool holder is positioned so it feeds as directly as possible into the extruder.

The top of spool holder needs to be very strong because all the torque of a 1Kg spool is applied there. It's angled at 30 degrees to reduce the torque somewhat, and so that the spool will be kept on the holder by gravity.

One extruder mount is designed for the stepper motor and extruder that I got with my printer. The other (added 15 Aug 2017) is designed for the stepper motor and extruder that came with my Diamond hotend.

The other motivation is that I'm planning on putting a Diamond 3-colour hotend on my printer; this way, I'll be able to have 3 spools and extruders on top of the printer, one on each side.

These will be usable for other deltas (or anything else with a 2040 profile). The Zonestar D810 has a 5mm acrylic plate on the top of the 2040 profile... other deltas may not, so you'll need to modify the design or add in 5mm of packing.

Spoolholder is printable on a 160mm bed.

As designed here, it's good for the front or right side of a delta. Mirror it if you want the spool to be on the left and removable from the front.

Still to come: a "universal" spool hub for spools with small holes (under 40mm) using F688ZZ bearings. Some of spools are very wide and have very small holes, so there's not enough room on the 150mm bolt for the quick-release nut.

Overview
Simple system with adjustable viewing angle to mount a Garmin 910XT via the standard wrist strap to 22mm diameter aerobar extensions. Accommodates inner bar spacing of 40 to 50mm as well as shifter cables running on the inner face of the aerobars.

Tools and Materials Required

  • 3mm x 3 to 6mm long or #3-48 x 1/8 to 1/4" long set screws for angle adjustment X2
  • 1.5mm(for m3) or 0.050"( for #3-48) hex key for set screws
  • 2.4mm or 3/32" (for m3) or 5/16" (for #3-48) drill bit to size set screw holes
  • m3 x 0.5 or #3-48 tap
  • Miniature Cable Ties (100mm/4" x 2.4mm/3/32" x 1mm/0.04") X4
  • Half round file ~12mm/1/2" and sharp knife for clean-up.

Printing

  • Print 2 of Garmin_Mount_Pin - recommend individually for best diameter consistency
  • Print 1 of either Garmin_Mount_Centre_Front_Adjust (pictured) or Rear_Adjust
  • Material: PETG recommended
  • Shell Thickness: 1.5 to 2mm
  • Infill: 10-15% should be plenty
  • Support: Not required if layer height is small. i used variable layer height from 0.32mm on the bottom of the pins to 0.16mm for the section with the cable tie passage (Slic3r) with a 0.5mm nozzle.

Assembly:

  • Size the angle adjustment holes and tap threads - remember PETG likes it slow, cool and needs frequent chip clean out in order to avoid rewarding you with a gummy mess. Note that you will likely have to bury the tap in order to get threads through to the bore of the centre piece but bear in mind that a snapped off tap in the work piece is a sad sight indeed.
  • Clean up the bore of the centre piece and outside of the centre pins ensuring pins fit freely but not loosely in centre piece and that the cable tie passages are reasonably clear..
  • Install a cable tie in each pin (a little judicious curving of the cable tie will help).
  • Push both pins fully into the centre piece.
  • Locate between extensions - note that oblong hole in centre piece faces up.
  • Add second cable ties and tighten firmly.
  • Mount watch - note that strap does not have to be tight - spare your spring pins
  • Adjust angle and fix by gently snugging set screws.

This is a minimalistic mount / adapter that helps mounting the tiny FrSky XM+ to a 36 x 36 mm flight controller.

It's best to print it in flexible materials (ideally TPU)

Note: This piece might also work with the FrSky XM, but given its smaller size it won't have as good of a grip on the receiver.

description.text:
I was flying my hyperlite floss with a runcam split but I was finding myself dropping frames more frequently than I would care to admit. The HD footage looked great but the frame drop was enough to make the quad hard to fly. With a bit of design work I was able to remix a gopro dummy into a suitable shell for the runcam split and while I was there I saved a bit of size and weight by scaling the whole operation down 75%.

Included in this thing is a scaled down session mount with a full scale hyperlite floss slot so the scaled down fauxpro session can still ride along the iconic floss top plate.

When Building be sure to run the runcam as far forward in this mount as possible because the FOV is extremely wide. A drop or 2 of hot glue along the front keeps the split from shifting position in the build.
Printed in CLear TPU and black PETG they are rather convincing when the quad flies past at 70-80MPH. Up close you can tell its the wrong size but its still a fun project.

description.text:
A folding frame quadcopter I made for testing some things. It's designed to house a KKMulticontroller fligth controller, RCTimer.com 2204-14 1400KV Outrunner Brushless Motors with 7 or 6 inch propeller (6" is better) and HobbyKing 12A BlueSeries Brushless Speed Controller (they press fit in place on the "medium" arms)

I haven't printed the fuselage fairing, but each half is meant to be printed vertically and then glued together. Instead of the fairing the roll bars provide protection to the top of the flight controller.  
The battery (2S 1500mAh) is held in place under the fuselage using two rubber bands  stretched between the landing gear legs, another pair of rubber bands hold the arms in the extended position.

Print the fuselage top and bottom, all holes are for M3 nylon screws, it's better to tap the holes on the fuselage top side but screws can be passed straight through and nuts used instead.  
Print two pair of arms, left and right (L & R), two copies of the landing gear and two of the rollbars.

description.text:
My O scale model train layout represents the section of the Pittsburgh & Lake Erie Railroad between McKees Rocks and Youngstown.

I modeled a 3D printed version of the P&LE's McKees Rocks Locomotive Shop, here:

OpenSCAD program: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2312384

Prototype photo: https://www.flickr.com/photos/dwdavidson/4880853220

I had to compress it lengthwise from 17 sections to 7 sections and I had to abbreviate the railroad name.

I learned from a member of the NYC Historical Society that the round newly painted bricks on each end of the prototype originally had a "New York Central System" logo. The P&LE was a wholly owned subsidiary of the NYC.

That logo was removed when the P&LE was given its independence when the NYC and Pennsy were merged to form the Penn Central.

In my alternate universe, the P&LE put their logo on the shops as the P&LE ran independently until 1992.

This thing is the P&LE logo. On my O scale model, a good size turned out to be 100mm in diameter. The 3D object was derived using the surface() OpenSCAD command along with a png version of the logo as found on the Internet. I created it as a 50mm circle originally so if you want a 100mm version, you will have to scale it up 200% in your slicer.

I used the 'cut' command in Slic3r to remove the background of the OpenSCAD stl file. I then created a 100mm background.

I printed the background using yellow PLA and I printed the rest of the logo in black. That way, I didn't have to paint it.

To use this in N, HO or G scale, you will have to scale appropriately.

/!\ WARNINGS FOR STUPID/LITIGIOUS PEOPLE: Rubber band gun intended for recreational purposes. Do not use in public. Wear eye protection. If shooting someone with rubber band guns, make sure they are sufficiently protected. I am not liable for any damages resulting from improper use of this rubber band gun. /!\

The LCAR (Low-Capacity Assault Rifle) is my second Lego RBG, with improvements to the functionality, appearance, and—not that it matters—rate of fire. I learned, at the expense of my nose, that those ABS pieces can only be taken so far. This gun is a spinoff of the Beretta ARX160 and Robinson Armament XCR. Just like before, spring the trigger with an average-sized rubber band (see picture). I also provided a breakdown file for more information about the mechanism and functions.

My next Lego gun should not be an automatic one; it takes a fraction of the reloading time to empty both of my auto RBGs.

STATS
Fire mode: automatic
Fire mechanism: repeater wheel regulated by escapement connected to sliding bolt
Capacity: 4 rounds
Ammo: size 18 or size 32 rubber bands (I actually use size 35)

FEATURES
Screw-operated ammo hook extension (do not point at or directly away from face)
More realistic appearance
Prop grenade launcher
Prop tactical flashlight
Two storage compartments: one in the prop mag and another in the grip (for the grip, pull out only the topmost of the two pins near the bottom).
Folding telescopic stock (can also be removed)
Charging handle can withstand more force than in the MRBG
Shoots up to 6 metres
Asymmetric components can easily swap sides to match user's handedness (stock pins, charging handle, prop flashlight)

TIPS

  • The notches in the pin connectors used in the trigger should face backwards, to better retain the rubber band that springs the trigger.

The end piece has a huge gap in it for the belt, which looks like it'll be hell to bridge/print -- and it is, it'll generate quite the mess.... which will all be hidden inside where you insert the belt anyways! So it's actually way less bad than it looks.

I finished the pieces with XTC-3D and Modern Metals Gold paint. The assembly was done with Gorilla clear epoxy. The round rod is 3/8" fiberglass, but nearly anything will work; the fiberglass is just what I had on hand. The gem is cast in EasyCast resin using a mold made from a 3" glass cabochon I found on Amazon. Feel free to adjust the model in F3D slightly if it doesn't match your cabochon. I also got a 3" round mirror from Joann's to put below the gem.

Since my gem didn't quite fit snugly, I printed a very simple retaining ring to put around it to hold it in with glue (so the glue didn't show below the gem).

In the photo of the finished belt, the belt itself is leather with vinyl/faux leather trim on top and bottom.

title: Wanhao i3 120mm PSU Fan Upgrade for Undermount

description.text:
I needed a 120mm fan upgrade for my Maker Select v2, as the stock 40mm fan makes a terrible grinding noise every time I turn the printer on. However, none of the options, by Kozar, worked for me. This is because I am mounting my control box under the table my printer is on! So I needed to flatten the top and increased the angle on the bottom to accommodate the 120mm fan.

I took some pictures of both the stock fan and it's replacement. As you can see in the pictures, the stock fan is tiny in comparison to the replacement. It moves about 9 f^3/m of air, whereas the replacement is rated at almost 70 f^3/m (at max RPM)! Even the most inexpensive 120mm fan will move around 30 f^3/m.

This is an extended back cover for the Wanhao Duplicator i3 PSU (also rebranded as Monoprice Maker Select, Balco 3D Printer, Cocoon Create). This model allows you to use a 120mm fan instead of the noisy tiny internal one. The new fan will be mounted outside of the power supply, but it will be much more silent. It adds about 10mm of extra length to the bottom.

I don't know if other versions of the printer have a different arrangement for the screw holes. This was designed for a v2.1 (v2 should be the same). Check compatibility for v1 and rebranded versions before printing.

The stock screws won't work for this part. Use M3x8mm or longer to attach the cover to your PSU case. Screw holes aren't countersunk (just counterbored), so choose screws with a flat top.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

It should be aligned with the PSU screw holes facing the build plate, already. Enable supports for the IEC connector/power switch plate and wiring loom slot.

It's not a must, but I recommend using 3 shells/solid perimeters for the holes where the fan mounts on, so when threading the screws the plastic doesn't break.

Installation guide
  1. Unplug the power cord from the wall socket and from the printer. Safety first!
  2. Unscrew the 4 black screws that hold the sheet metal back cover in place. Save them if you plan to reinstall the stock cover in the future (they are too short to work with this mod).
  3. The cable loom going from the control box to the printer goes through a cut in the back plate and is held by a zip tie. Cut that zip tie to free the loom from the plate.
  4. Disconnect the spade connectors going to the IEC power socket + switch combo. Notice the wire colors and location to reinstall them later in the correct position. Take a picture if necessary.
  5. Disconnect the small fan from the power supply.
  6. Unscrew the fasteners holding the socket/switch in place. You should be able to lift it off the plate (use a flat screwdriver as leverage if you need so to get it out).
  7. Position the back cover and align it with the screw holes tapped in the case of the control box. Make sure the wire loom goes through the U-shaped cut-out provided.
  8. Use M3x8mm or longer to attach the plate to the metal case.
  9. Take the wires that were attached to the IEC connector/switch and guide them through the rectangular cutout provided (located on the top or sides, depending on the model you have printed). Re-attach the wires to the switch and screw it in back. You can reuse the stock screws that came with it (be gentle when doing this, you're threading into plastic).
  10. Take your 120mm fan and use the +12v and GND wires to connect it to the psu. If your fan has a molex connector (3 or 4 pin) you should be able to just plug the cable in to the existing connector you left coming from the power supply.
  11. You may want to use some electrical tape or a drop of hot glue to secure the connection.
  12. Align the fan with the mounting holes of the printed cover. Use M4x40mm screws or self-tappers of similar length to secure the fan to the cover. Make sure to tidy all the cables up inside so they don't catch on the fan blades.
  13. Enjoy your silent printer!
Extra

I recommend the addition of a fan grill to protect your fingers from the spinning blades. It is one of the drawbacks of having the fan exposed instead of inside the case. Be careful!

description.text:
This is a big eyelet for use with the Shallotte belt (~1.5 inches wide on the visible outside piece!!!). See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2468746 for some other belt pieces.

I made this because I didn't have on hand anything close to the right sort of eyelet size I'd need for this belt (it's huge!) so I applied my usual hammer and 3D printed it.

I designed the tolerances in this such that you can fairly easily snap it on and off a ~1.5mm-2mm thick piece of leather, but it still holds quite strongly. It works fine with PLA despite PLA's very high stiffness, but I can easily imagine it would work as well or better with a more flexible material like ABS.

title: Ultralight Fly Fishing Reel
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is another Fly Reel I designed a few years ago. This one is Ultralight Design and was designed and paired this with a cheap Eagle Claw Featherlight 3/4 Line Weight Fly Rod I found on Amazon.

Let me start by saying I know very little about fly fishing and not a damn thing about fly reel design. Much like my other printed fly reel I made this just to see if I could.

This is a simple Click and Pawl design reel - it uses a spring, ball, and dents designed into the spool to control the very "limited" drag. It was designed to use your hand against the outer spools rim if you need more drag.

Notice - If your looking at this think it would be a cheap way to get into fly fishing I highly recommend going another route. Shorter/lighter fly rods are harder to cast... get something better/larger or you will just get frustrated and quit.

Ok.... with all that out of the way on to the nuts and bolts....

Hardware Required

  • (1) 10-32 x 1" Socket Head Screw and Nut (See Notes Below)
  • (1) 4-40 x 1/2" Flat Head Screw
  • (1) Thrust Bearing (or washers See Notes Below)
  • (1) Spring & Ball
     

Notes

Nut-
The nut for the spool is embedded into the actual thumb knob during printing and requires a thin nut. (I used a 18-8 Stainless Steel Thin Nylon-Insert Locknut from Mcmaster Item# 90101A225) You could probably just use a nut and washer but seeing it's used to set the drag of the reel (so to speak) it might be hard to adjust in the field without a tool if you went that route.

If you can not find a thin nut I have included two different thumb nut files to choose from....
Ultralight_Fly_Reel_Thumb_Nut.STL uses a Thin Nylon-Insert Locknut with with these specs
Ultralight_Fly_Reel_Thumb_Nut_Full.STL uses a full sized Nylon-Insert Locknut with with these specs

Thrust Bearing
Unfortunately I made this so long ago I don't remember were I bought the thrust bearing from. (probably eBay) The thrust bearing setup measures .472" (12mm) Width x .176" (4.5mm) height. (you could probably substitute a few plain washers in place of the thrust bearing.)

Spring and Ball
The spring and ball for the clicker/drag can be a Pen Spring and a BB but they will rust over time. I used a .186" chrome ball (Honda Motorcycle Part# 96211-06000) and I also used a cut down stainless steel spring I found locally. Use a small hex wrench to press the spring and ball into the hole while pressing the spool down then just remove the hex wrench and the spool should fit into place holding the ball. It's a little tricky but not impossible. Hold the spool in place untill you tighten the thumb knob.

Misc.
The hole for the spool bolt was left small and tapped with a 10-32 tap. (You can probably just force the screw in but it might crack.) The Handle pin was also tapped for the 4-40 screw.

Printing

Printing this reel is a little more difficult to print than my other fly reel because of all the curved surfaces. This was as much test for me in printing as it was reel design.

Everything was printed in the orientation shown in the STl previews. The spools halves will take a lot more support this way but I wanted the outer surfaces to look the best I could get them. The inner spool surfaces where sanded smoother to keep any excess wear from happening to the fly line.

If you have any questions or problems with the files or fitment of the parts just let me know and I will try to fix them.

Remember if to tip your waiters designers if you like the service.... thanks for looking
